Todayâ€™s SQL problem helped me strengthen my understanding of JOIN + GROUP BY + Derived Tables.

ðŸ”Ž Problem:
Find employees who earn the highest salary in each department.

ðŸ’¡ Instead of using a correlated subquery, I used a more optimized approach:

1ï¸âƒ£ First, calculate the maximum salary per department
2ï¸âƒ£ Then, join it back with the Employee table
3ï¸âƒ£ Finally, filter employees whose salary matches the departmentâ€™s maximum

Hereâ€™s the solution I implemented:

SELECT d.name AS Department,
       e.name AS Employee,
       e.salary AS Salary
FROM Employee e
JOIN Department d
  ON e.departmentId = d.id
JOIN (
    SELECT departmentId, MAX(salary) AS max_salary
    FROM Employee
    GROUP BY departmentId
) m
ON e.departmentId = m.departmentId
AND e.salary = m.max_salary;


ðŸ§  Key Learnings:

How GROUP BY helps aggregate data

How derived tables (subqueries in JOIN) work

Writing more efficient queries instead of correlated subqueries

Handling cases where multiple employees share the same highest salary

